tandard critic's $V_A(s)$. The residual $f_\\theta(s)$ is non-zero, indicating the network learned meaningful corrections to the Lyapunov prior.}\n    \\label{fig:heatmaps}\n\\end{figure}\n\nThis qualitative observation is confirmed quantitatively. The Mean Squared Error (MSE) between the standard critic's value function and the Lyapunov function was $\\text{MSE}(V_A, \\Phi) = 71.98$. The structured critic's value function reduced this error by 86\\% to an MSE of just 10.07. This demonstrates that the structural prior successfully constrained the learned value function to be much closer to the analytical, energy-based form.\n\nHowever, the learned residual component $f_\\theta(s)$ in the structured critic was not negligible, as shown in Figure~\\ref{fig:heatmaps}d. The MSE of 10.07 for Condition B is entirely attributable to this learned residual. We found that the mean absolute value of the residual, $|f_\\theta(s)|$, across the state grid was approximately 26\\% of the mean value of $\\Phi(s)$. This indicates that the network learned a non-trivial correction to the Lyapunov prior, likely to account for deviations between the true value function of the agent's suboptimal policy and the ideal energy landscape.\n\n\\subsection{Lyapunov prior accelerates critic learning}\nTo understand the mechanism behind the improved value function alignment, we analyzed the most direct measure of critic learning: its training loss. This loss is the mean squared error between the critic's value predictions $V(s)$ and the empirical returns computed via Generalized Advantage Estimation (GAE).\n\nAs shown in Figure~\\ref{fig:critic_loss_plot} and Table~\\ref{tab:critic_loss}, the Lyapunov-structured critic (Condition B) achieved a dramatically lower training loss. The overall mean loss for Condition B was 0.136, an 87\\% reduction compared to the 1.057 loss of the standard critic (Condition A). The benefit was most pronounced in the early stages of training (the first 20\\% of updates)